Fraudulent Transaction Detection Project
Introduction
Financial institutions face enormous losses from fraudulent transactions. To help stakeholders see tangible results, this project demonstrates end to end skills from data ingestion to deployment using a synthetic dataset of 1,000 transactions 
with just 45 flagged as fraud. The objective was to predict fraudulent transactions by combining 10 diverse CSV files (account activity, customer and merchant attributes, anomaly scores and more) into a single analysis pipeline, cleaning the data,
exploring relationships, balancing imbalanced classes with SMOTE, evaluating several machine learning algorithms with robust metrics, and building an interactive dashboard for business users.
Data consolidation and cleaning
The ten CSV files obtained from Kaggle (https://www.kaggle.com/datasets) were loaded with pandas and merged using common keys such as TransactionID, CustomerID and MerchantID. The resulting consolidated_transactions.csv contains 17 fields and 
1,000 records; there were no missing values. Important variables include:
•	TransactionID (identifier) 
•	Amount/TransactionAmount (monetary value) 
•	AnomalyScore (numeric anomaly score from a separate model) 
•	Category (transaction category from transaction_category_labels) 
•	Timestamp (date and time) 
•	Customer demographics: CustomerID, Name, Age, Address, AccountBalance, LastLogin 
•	Merchant data: MerchantID, MerchantName, Location 
•	FraudIndicator: target variable where 1 marks a fraudulent transaction and 0 a normal one 
The cleaning phase involved:
1.	Parsing dates and extracting temporal features: Timestamp was converted to datetime. New features derived included hour of transaction, day of week and month; days since last login were computed from LastLogin. 
2.	Dropping high cardinality attributes: features such as Name and Address were removed because their high uniqueness can cause overfitting and are privacy sensitive. 
3.	Target definition: FraudIndicator was used as the dependent variable (1 for fraud, 0 for normal); all other variables were treated as independent. 
4.	Class imbalance check – The merged dataset contained only 45 frauds vs. 955 normal transactions (≈4.5 % fraud rate), creating a highly imbalanced problem. 
Exploratory data analysis
Descriptive statistics showed that fraudulent transactions tended to have slightly higher median amounts and anomaly scores, but the overlap with normal transactions was significant. A correlation matrix was visualized using 
a heatmap to examine linear relationships. Positive correlations were observed between Amount and AccountBalance, while the FraudIndicator showed only weak correlations with numerical features, suggesting that linear models 
alone may not separate fraud well. This justifies trying non linear models and more sophisticated techniques.
Handling imbalanced data using SMOTE
Because fraudulent transactions constituted only 4.5 % of the data, training a classifier on the raw dataset risked biasing the model toward the majority class. Synthetic Minority Oversampling Technique (SMOTE) was applied to the training folds. 
SMOTE synthetically generates new minority (fraud) examples by interpolating between existing fraud samples in feature space. This process continues until the class distribution becomes balanced. Oversampling was performed only on the training data 
within each cross validation fold to prevent information leakage.
Model building and evaluation
To extract value from the cleaned data, a machine learning pipeline was created using scikit learn and imblearn. The column transformer encoded categorical features (one hot encoding), scaled numerical features (StandardScaler), 
and passed them to a SMOTE oversampler followed by a classifier. A Stratified 5 fold cross validation ensured that both classes appeared in each fold. Six algorithms were compared:
1.	Logistic Regression – baseline linear classifier. 
2.	Random Forest – ensemble of decision trees. 
3.	Gradient Boosting – sequential tree boosting. 
4.	Decision Tree – interpretable single tree. 
5.	K Nearest Neighbors (KNN) – non parametric, uses distance in feature space. 
6.	Support Vector Machine (RBF kernel) – non linear decision boundary. 
Evaluation metrics
Imbalanced classification requires metrics that reflect the minority class. The following metrics were used:
•	Precision – the proportion of predicted frauds that are truly fraudulent. It equals true positives divided by the sum of true positives and false positives. 
•	Recall (sensitivity) – the proportion of actual frauds that the model correctly identifies. It equals true positives divided by true positives plus false negatives. 
•	F1 score – harmonic mean of precision and recall; it provides a single summary that balances both metrics. 
•	Precision Recall AUC (PR AUC) – area under the precision recall curve. For imbalanced datasets, the PR curve is more informative than ROC because it focuses on correctly detecting the minority class. High precision and high recall correspond to 
  few false positives and few false negatives. A high PR AUC indicates a strong classifier. 
•	Receiver Operating Characteristic AUC (ROC AUC) – area under the ROC curve, which plots the true positive rate against the false positive rate across thresholds. A perfect model has ROC AUC = 1 and a random classifier has 0.5. 
