While KNN achieved higher recall, it still produced many false positives (low precision), highlighting that the feature set may not be rich enough to discriminate fraud. Most models predicted no fraud at all (zero recall) 
due to the small sample of fraudulent examples. Additional features such as device information, velocity of transactions or network anomalies could improve performance.
Validation and deployment considerations
Validation using stratified cross validation helped to assess generalization on unseen data. Before deploying to production, it is essential to:
1.	Use an independent test set to estimate performance on new data not used during model training or oversampling. 
2.	Monitor model drift and retrain periodically as fraud patterns evolve. 
3.	Implement threshold tuning based on business objectives (e.g., high recall to catch fraud vs. high precision to minimize false alerts). 
4.	Explainability and governance – regulatory requirements may demand interpretable models; using tree based models or SHAP values can provide explanations. 
After selecting the best model (KNN in this experiment), it can be exported using joblib or pickle and wrapped in a REST API for real time scoring. The pipeline should replicate preprocessing (feature engineering, encoding, SMOTE for training only)
to ensure consistency.
Interactive dashboard
An interactive dashboard was built with Plotly Dash and saved as fraud_detection_dashboard.html. The dashboard enables recruiters or business users to explore fraud patterns:
•	Bar chart showing the number of fraud and non fraud transactions per category. 
•	Violin plot comparing the distribution of transaction amounts for fraudulent vs. normal transactions. 
•	Scatter plot of anomaly score versus transaction amount coloured by fraud label to identify outliers. 
•	KPI panel summarizing key statistics such as total transactions, number of fraud cases, and fraud rate. Filters allow users to slice by category or merchant location. (In the provided implementation, some layout adjustments are needed to avoid 
  overlapping KPI values.) 
The dashboard helps non technical stakeholders understand patterns and supports interactive exploration of the data, which is attractive to recruiters seeking evidence of data visualization skills.
Challenges encountered
Several issues arose during the project:
1.	Class imbalance – With only 45 fraud cases, most algorithms predicted the majority class. SMOTE mitigated the problem but did not overcome the fundamental limitation of sparse fraud examples. 
2.	Feature sparsity and weak correlations – The available features showed little correlation with the fraud label. Real world fraud detection often requires more complex behavioural features (transaction velocity, device fingerprinting, IP geolocation). 
    Without such data, predictive power was limited. 
3.	Dashboard layout – Plotly’s make_subplots required careful domain assignment for the KPI indicator; the initial version had overlapping KPI text. This can be improved by adjusting row heights or creating dedicated KPI widgets. 
4.	Data merging and cleaning – Combining ten datasets required careful alignment on keys; mismatches could have introduced duplicates or mislabelled transactions. Additionally, dropping high cardinality fields was necessary to prevent overfitting and protect privacy. 

Ranked feature sensitivity (higher implies more influence on the fraud prediction): AnomalyScore, TransactionAmount, AccountBalance, Age, DaysSinceLastLogin, TransactionCategory, MerchantLocation, MerchantID. Names and addresses were excluded to protect privacy.

Conclusion
This project showcases a complete fraud detection pipeline. It involved merging multi source data, creating new features, dealing with class imbalance using SMOTE, evaluating multiple algorithms with metrics suitable for imbalanced classification, 
and delivering insights through an interactive dashboard. Although the models struggled due to limited and weakly informative features, the process demonstrates competence in data engineering, exploratory analysis, model selection, metric interpretation, 
visualization and deployment considerations. With richer data and continuous monitoring, such a system could be refined into a powerful fraud detection service.
